{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_jamaica_ver02/data/sn83030214/00175039314/1908033101/0618.xml":{"full_text":"New-Dork Tribune,\nVoL LXVIL Ne Sraie. mom vem rw NEW.YORK. TUESDAY. MARCH 31. 1905_TWELVE PAGES\u2014_ nfm. PRICE THREE CENTS.\n1908, by\nAssociation.\nMOVE AGAINST JACKSON\nPRESENTMENT BY JURY.\nAttorney General Calls It \u201cLying.\nCowardly, Contem ptible Trick.\u201d\nThe March grand jury for New York County\npanded up to Judge Foster, of the Court of Gen\nera) Sessions, late yesterday afternoon, a pre\ngentment against Attorney General Jackson. In\nst the jury stated that evidence had been given\npefore it reflecting upon the integrity of the\nAttermey General and that there was an apparent\ncemflict of evidence, and for this reason and be\ncause of the \u201ctranscendent importance\u201d of the\nAttorney General's office, the jury requested that\ncopies of the presentment and the evidence be\ngent tn\u00bb Governor Hughes, the President of the\ngenate and the Speaker of the Assembly.\nNews of the grand jury's action enraged Mr.\nJackson. \u201cI call it a lying, dirty, cowardly, con\ntemptible trick.\u201d he indignantly asserted, \u201cand\n1 think the grand jurors ought to be punished\nfor contempt of court. It looks to me like a\ncontemptible attempt to defame and discre iit\nme before the people of this state. They say\nthere has been conflicting testimony. From my\n4nformation that statement is a lie.\u201d\nThe Attorney General said he would go before\nJudge Foster this morning and move that the\npresentment be expunged from the records on\nthe grounds that it is \u201ctotally illegal, unwar\nranted and scandalous.\u201d It is believed that Mr.\nJackson will attempt also to prevent the sending\nof copies to the Governor and the presiding offi\ncers of the Legislature. Mr. Jackson may try to\nhave the jurors punished for contempt.\nIn accepting the presentment Judge Foster\nsaid: 1 received from the Attorney General a\ncommunication stating that he desired me to\ngive him an opportunity to make a motion in\ncourt to expunge the presentment from the rec\nord before it was made public, on the ground\nthat it contained illegal and scandalous mat\nter.\n\u201cOf course, this presentment will be received\nand placed on file, and later it wiil be determined\nas to what course it shall take. I don\u2019t know\nmyself whether this instrument should be called\npresentment or a communication. It repre\ngents a presenument in your judgment and it is\nentitled to consideration. For that purpose it\nwill take its usual course.\u201d\n\nThe presentment was signed by William C.\nMuschenheim, foreman of the grand jury, and\nGeorge 8. Terry, secretary. It follows:\nTestimony has been given before the grand\njury affecting the integrity of the Attorney Gen\neral of the state, and an opportunity has been\nextended him to appear before this body. The\nAttorney General testified and there now ap\npears a conflict of testimony in respect to the\nmaiter brought before us.\n\n\nThe office of Attorney General is one of such\ntranscendant importance in the administration\n\u00abf the business of the state, and the confidence\nof the peiple of the state in the integrity of the\nAttorney .General is so essential to public wel\nfare, that we deem it our duty to respectfully\ncall the situation to vour honer\u2019s attention and\nrequest vou to direct the clerk of the court to\ntransmit this presentinent ang a copy of the tes\ntimony and proceedings before this grand jury\nto his excellency the Governor of this state, the\nPresident of the Senate and the Speaker of the\nAssembly for action.\n\n\nMr. Jackson. in explaining his statement that\nthe grand jury had no legal right to hand up a\npresentment against him. szid:\n\u201cThe powers of the grand jury are defined\nboth by statute and the constitution. A grand Jury\ncan hand up a presentment only after it has ex\nercised its inquisitorial powers. It may exercise\nthese powers by investigating a public official\nfor wilfu! misconduct or corruption in office. It\ncannot legally hand up a presentment in this\ncase because it has not made and it does not\nclzim to have made an investigation of me or\nmy official conduct. Its sole duty in this in\nstance was to vote upon whether or not a true\nbill or an indiciment be found against me.\n\n\n\n\u201cIf itedid not have sufficient evidence upon\nwhich te base an indictment that should, under\nhe lzw. have ended the matter. There is no\negal justification for a grand jury after it has\niled to find an indictment against a man 10\nnd up a presentment which reflects upon him,\nznd which reflection he is of necessity powerless\n1n remove That is just what a grand jury is\nsupposed to prevent, injustice of that sort.\u201d\n\nMr Jackson quoted from an opinion of Justice\nWoodward of ihe Appeilate Division, 2d De\npartment. in which the Justice said- \u201cIt seems\n10 me clear that there is no constitutionai right\nto mike a presentment against an individual in\ncase where an indictment would not lie If\nthere has been no crime or offence the grand\nie]\nty\nAl\njury designed for the protection of a citizen has\nro right to create an offence unknown to the law\nfor purposes of punishing by censure, \u2018for this\ni\n\nbe\nRE)\nis 2 government of laws and not of men.\nTHIS WAS THE WRONG HUNTER.\nPolice Enter Meeting, but Find James T.,\nLaundry Worker. Not Robert. Socialist.\nSr\n\nThe police, thinking that a meeting was a cloak\nfor 3 gathering of anarchists, and supposing that\nBobers Hunter was to speak, descended last even\ning on the Independent Laundry Workers of New\nYork in Manhattan Hall, No 3516 East 62d street.\n2 letter cioned \u201cThe Hawkins\u201d =ent to Captain\nares of the j.ast 67ih street station. had misled\nthem\n\n\n\n\nRhen <ix police nWcers, including a lieutenant\n2:4 sergeant, reached the hall, they found that\none of ihe executives of the Laundry Workers,\nJares T Hunter, was to address the meeting, in\nstead of Robert Hunter. and that the meeting had\nbeer, called to invite the ironers of the city to\nJoin 1he orgamzation. The officers at first could\naut realize that tne meting was innocent, and\nthe members of the organization say that many\nof them were searched for weapons.\n\n\n\nCEILD KILLED IN SAVING BROTHER.\nSchoclboy Here Crushed by Trolley Car in\nFast New York.\nYs saving his brother Gussie from being killed\ntt 2 Faigh avonue trolley car last night Isidor\nRoger, 1melve ears old, of No 631 Rockaway\n#venve, Fast Nem York. lost his life as the ve\nsult of nis heroism. isidor and Gussie were re\nturning honae from az Hebrew gchool. and had to\n\u20ac1osg the ear 1racks to reach their home. As the\nbors crossed the tracks car No. 1.817, of the Ralph\n\u00aeienue Hine, struck isidor, who pushed Lis brother\nGussie out of danger\n\ni\n\n\n\n\nAn furizicd crowd gathered around Patrick\nyastorman of the car, and started in to\nhim. (ne man <truck Brennan over the\n\u00aehoulders with a club. Brennan managed to clear\nhimgelf from the crowd after a while and run to\nWerther car, which tock him io the Canarsie Larus.\n\nFier\nPomme\n\n\n#21 the car Larns the police told Breanan to\nClunpe hie uniform, for fesr of another outbreak.\nPrerman was (hen taken to the Brownsviile station\ni 2 rar. where a charge of homicide was enterad\nREainst hin dttle Isidor's hody was also 1ken\n1) he station Louse, after being pronounced bfe\ngs 10 Tr afurehy of Si. Mary's Hospital.\n\n\nSWISS TUNNEL. FIVE MILES LONG, DONE.\ni\nBerne Switgeriand, March 30. The federal 150\nTed tunnel through the Ricken Mountaias, near\nlaze Zurich, was completed to-day. onstruction\n\u00a9a the tunnel, which is nearly five miles long, was\nbegun four veers ago.\n\n\nDEWEY'S PURE GRAPZ JUICE.\nilies the Rlood and is very Nourishing.\nBE I Tews Sons Cc., 138 Fulton St, New York\nDEWEY'S PURE GRAPZ\nGOVERNOR COMING HERE.\nS poke Befolk Herkimer Business\nMen Last Night.\nUtica. N. Y., March 30.\u2014@\u00aeovernor Hughes\nwas. the guest of hortor and the principal\nspeaker at the third annual banquet of the\nHerkimer Business Men's Association to-night.\nThe Governor arrived here at 6:35 o'clock, and\nwas met by a large committee from Herki\n\u201cmer. A special trolley car took the party to\nthat place, where many windows were adorned\nwith large pictures of Mr. Hughes bearing th\u00ae\nwords \u201cWelcome to Our Governor.\u201d\nAfter his twenty minutes\u2019 speech, Mr. Hughes\ncame to Utica and boarded a train after mid\nnight for New York, where he is to remain to\nmorrow, because of the primaries.\nIn his speech Governor Hughes said in part:\nThis is a good day for the business men. we\nare having a temporary depression, but it cannot\nlast. Conditions are such in this country that\n1 believe the return of prosperity is sure in the\nnear future. It is a good day because it is a\ntime of simplification and consideration, a time\nwhen the demagogue abroad in the land has the\nleast possible chance of a hearing. 1 believe\nwe are learning rapidly to appreciate the fact\nthat our problems are too important to be dealt\n\u201cwith hastily, that facts must be considered and\nanalyzed and their solution is not in thoughtless\nranks, but in the exercise of the best judgment,\nso that the fair demands of the people may be\nmet and at the same time the country may do\nits work and prosper.\nIt is a fact that large business enterprises are\n\u201cmore careful than for a long time, and that they\nseek to make their programme square with what\nis equitable. Action is being taken on the de\nmands being made that business shall be man\naged in an honorable way. There is an increas\ning desire for fair and practical consideration,\nand in this approach. with reason on one hand\nand a desire to be fair on the other hand, no\nquestion is so difficult but that a fair solution\nof it will be reached.\nThere is no abatement whatever of insistence\non the part of the people that the rights of the\npeople shall dominate; that no interest shall be\nsuperior to the public interest: that there is a\ngrowing appreciation of the fact that vou can\nnot sprinkle sand in our mechanism and expect\nit to work. It is a day when business men may\nlook forward with a greater confidence than in\na long time, because the whole American peo\nple are more intelligently considering the ques\ntions of difficulty. There is a desire on the part\nof every one that no injustice shall be done, but\nthat justice shall everywhere prevail.\nMINERS QUIT TO-NIGHT.\nZapiration of Coal Contracts Will\nMale 250.000 Men Idie.\n\nIndianapolis, March 30.\u2014The union miners in\nmost of the coal fields of the country will lay\ndown their tools to-morrow night. Almost two\nhundred and fifty thousand will stop work in\nOhio, Western Pennsylvania, Missouri, Iowa.\nKansas, Oklahoma, Arkansas, Texas, and prob\nably in Indiana, Illinois, Michigan, West Vir\nginia and Kentucky. The mining contracts un\nder which they are now working expire at mid\nright to-morrow night, and, except in Central\nPennsylvania and in the Indiana block coal dis\ntrict, no contracts have been made nor have the\nminers and operators vet entered into district\nagreements providing for the operation of the\nmines after April 1, pending agreement.\n\nThis is a possibility in the Indiana bituminous\ncoal district, in Illinois, Michigan and West Vir\nginia. The Indiana bituminous, Western Penn\nsivania and I\u2122nocis miners and operators are in\njoint session at Terre Haute, Pittsburg and\nSpringfield.\nTechnically. the miners will go out on strike,\nbut in reality they stop work because the oper\nators, except in Indiana and Illinois, show no\nreal intention of meeting and treating with\nthem, though no question of wage or principie\nis at stake.\n\n\nPittsburg. March 30.\u2014T. TY. Lewis, the newly\nelected president of the United Mine Workers, has\nbeen requested to come to Pittsburg to attend a\njoint conference of miners and operators tomor\nrow, at which it will be decided whether the mines\nin the Western Pennsylvania district will be closed\ndown to-morrow night pending a settlement of\nthe wage question. The miners are said to be\nwilling to continue operations after April 1, provid\ning negotiations are not broken off by the oper\nators. Both sides have appointed scale commit\ntees, who will meet in joint session to-morrow.\n\n\nPittsburg. March 30.\u2014T. L. Lewis, the newly\nelected president of the United Mine Workers, has\nbeen requested to come to Pittsburg to attend a\njoint conference of miners and operators tomor\nrow, at which it will be decided whether the mines\nin the Western Pennsylvania district will be closed\ndown to-morrow night pending a settlement of\nthe wage question. The miners are said to be\nwilling to continue operations after April 1, provid\ning negotiations are not broken off by the oper\nators. Both sides have appointed scale commit\ntees, who will meet in joint session to-morrow.\nWINKIPEG TO TRY CITY OWNERSHIP.\nDecides to Expend $13.000.000 for Street\nBailwavs. Lighting and Pewer Plants.\nWinnipeg. Man.. March 30.\u2014The City Council of\nWinnipeg decided to-night to buy from the Mac\nkenzie and Mann interests the street r#flwavs\nwithin the city limite. These properties include\nthirty miles of electric railway, an electric\nlight plant and an electric power plant, forty-five\nmiles from the city, which supplies power to in\ndustries., will also be purchased. The sale, based\non quotations of stock in Toronto to-day, will in\nvolve about $13,000,000\nThe city is developing 2 magnificent power plant\non Winnipeg River, sixty miles from the city, at\na cost of $5,600,000. The City Council appointed to\nnight a committee to complete the negotiations.\nThe franchise of the street railway company has\nnineteen years to run.\ni\n\nPOLICEMAN HURT CHASING AN AUTO.\nA fruitless automobile chase in the upper Ten\ncerlein last niznt resulted in serious injury to Al\nbert Bernard, a bicvele policeman, who followed a\nred touring ear from Seventh avenue and 434 street\ntn 38th street, when his hievele slipped and threw\nim in the path of a3 cab. In the automobile were\ntne men and two wcecmen, who were smoking\nclrareties,\nHER\n\n\nThe policeman gave chasf, and was about to ar\nrest the autemobilists when he was thrown, in\nfront of the ilotel Navarre. Bernard was taken\nthe New York Hospital.\nHUGE STONE CRASHES INTO A CAR.\nA stone weighing severa hundred pounds rolied\noff the top of un embankment, 100 feet high, sur\nrounding the High Schoiel at the head of Sth\nstreet. Jerscy (ity, last night, and crashed into a\n\n\ncrowded Pavenia avenue trolley car. Miss lucy\nHarney, a public school teacher, of No. 2% Pa\nvonia avenue, was severely shocked. She was\n\nassisted to her home by passengers in the car.\n\nThe stone was probably loosened by the jarring\nof West Shore Railroad trains that run along the\nhattan: of the embankment.\n{\u2014y Telegraph to The Tribune.)\nPoston, March 30. Mr. Bryan has lost one of his\nmost stalwart supporters in Henry M. Whitney, the\nmillionaire reciprocity leader of this city, who\ncame out to-day in favor of the nomination of\n(ravernor Johnson of Minnesota.\nindianapolis, March 4%. Express rates in Indiana\nare reduced between 10 and 12 per cent in an opin\norder issued to-day by the Indiana Ral\nThe new schedule is (0 be adapt\n\n\nyanies within thirty days. Th\u00bb\ncompanies in\njon and\nroad Commission.\neG by express cong\nto:a: annual business of all express\nthe state is about $1,000,000, according to mforma\nec-ed by the commission.\ntion\n~ipTY HANDS OF ATLANTA CONDUCTORS.\nef\n{By Telegraph to The Tribune.\nAtlanta, March 30. Help oid ladies in black\ndresses, but leave the young Ones with white and\nlight colored shirtwaists to get un the cars unas\nsisted,\u201d was the appeal made to the street car\nauthorities here to-day by Mrs. Maria Sprink'e,\nans aeclares that her weisl \u201cds rulticu wy the\n\ndirt hands of conductors,\nHENRY M. WHITNEY FCR JOHNSON.\nINDIANA EXPRESS RATES CUT.\ner\nHOME RULE ADVANCED\nWINS POINT IN COMMONS.\nRedmond\u2019s Resolution Favoring Adu\ntonomy Adopted After Amendment.\nLondon, March 30.\u2014The House of Commons\nto-night, after a long debate on the question of\nHome Rule for Ireland, adopted by a vote of\n313 to 157 a resolution, moved by Jchn E. Red\nmond, the Natiogalist leader, that \u201cin the\nopinion of this house a solution of this problem\ncan only be attained by giving tae Irish people\nlegislative and executive control of all purely\nIrish affairs,\u201d after it had been amended by\nadding the words \u201call subject to the supreme\nauthority of the imperial Parliament.\u201d\nIt was known beforehand that the debate\ncould have only an academic intcrest, because\nthe government already had pledged that there\nwould be no deal in the matter of Home Rule\nuntil it had received a mandate at the general\nelection. But the debate was made notable\nthrough the strong declaration of Counsellor\nAsquith, which was all the weightier because\nmade at the moment Mr. Asquith was actually\nassuming the Premiership.\nMr. Balfour, in a brief speech, had accused\nhis opponents of speaking with two meanmgs,\na Radical meaning and a Nationalist meaning.\nHe asked how it was conceivably possible to\ncarry out great Irish reforms with British\nmoney except by a British Parliament, and\nironically challenged Mr. Asquith to clear up\nthis ambiguity. Amid Unionist laughter, Mr.\nAsquith rose and sald that never in his life had\nhe felt less embarrassed. For over twenty years\nhe himself and his colleagues had steadily and\nconsistently advocated self-government fer Ire\nland's purely local affairs. He held that opinion\nnow as strongly as ever. He could not, how\never. support Mr. Redmond\u2019s motion in its pres\nent form, because he found in it no explicit rec\nognition of imperial supremacy, and, further,\nbecause no Parliament would be justified in\nembarking in such a task unless the matter\nfirst had been submitted to the electorate. It\nwould be a gross and inexcusable violation of\ntheir promises, he said, to do so in the lifetime\nof the present Parliament, and as far as the\npresent Parliament was concerned it had\nexhausted its powers in regard to the problem\nof Irish government in the Irish councils bill\nlast vear.\n\nTimothy Healy closed the debate, declaring\nthat Mr. Asquith was mistaken if he supposed\nhe would commend himself to the Irish nation\nby \"his speech.\nEarl Percy, on behalf of the Unionists, moved\nan amendment declaring the House to be un\nalterably opposed to the creation of an Irish\nParliament with a responsible executive, but\nthe amendment was rejected.\nEDWIN GOULD, OPTIMIST\nWestern Maryland and VW abash\nPlans Will Be Carried Out.\nBaltimore, March 30.\u2014Edwin Gould, who arrived\nin Baltimore to-night from the South, declared\npositively that there had been ne change in the\noriginal plans to make the Western Maryland the\neastern outlet of the Wabash or in the determina\ntion to finish the Pittsburg extension.\n\u201cWe are,\u201d he said, \u201cjust as anxious as ever to\nhold on to Baltimore, but the realization of that\npurpose depends on the completion of the Pitts\nburg link.\n\u201cPittsburg will be reached sooner or later. The\npossibilities for the Wabash are entirely too great\nand we cannot abandou this great improvement.\n\u201cThe appointment of a receiver will, of course,\ncause some delay, but a great deal depends on the\nmoney market.\n\u201cPersonally I think railroad securities the best\ninvestments in the world. I am not frightened by\na flurry in the money market, and this confidence\nseems to pervade all the directors and stockholders\nof the Western Maryland.\u201d\nRILEY GRANNAN DANGEROUSLY ILL\nSpectacular Plunger May Not Be Able to\nRecover frem Pneumonia.\nSan Francisco, Marca 30. A private dis\npatch from Rawhide. the new mining camp of\nNevada, says that Riley Grannan, the well known\nturf plunger, has pneumonia and cannot recover.\nGrannan went into Rawhide with the first rush,\nbut has devoted himself to gambling, as he was\nnot physically able to get out and do prospecting.\nOn March 15 he played roulette in Carl Young's\ngambling house, and soon began to stake $1,000 on\nthe turn of the whee!. He won $2000, and as the\nbank was broke, he induced Young to put up his\nsaloon. Grannan lorct.\nHe is said to be a nervous wreck, which will\nmake it hard for him to survive pneumonia.\nWOMAN HELD UP NEAR \u201cL\u201d STATION\nDragged into Hallway, Strangled and Con\ntents of Handbag Taken from Her.\nThe screams of Miss Helen Lendhal, a dress\nmaker, of No. 428 East 165th street attracted the\nattention of policemen last night, and when they\nsaw a man running away from the \u201cL\u2019' station at\nThird avenue and 15th street, they gave chase and\ncaptured him.\nReturning. they found Miss I.endhal lying on the\nstairs of the station in a state of exhaustion. She\nsaid the man had attacked her as she was about to\n~srend the stairs and had dragged her to a nearby\ndoorway. There she sald he strangled her and took\nthe contents of her handbag. Then he knocked her\ndown.\nThe prisoner, who sald he was Frank iudson, of\nNo. 402 East 21st street, was taken {o the East 224\nstreet police station and held on a charge of high\nway robbery. Sixty cents and a pair of scissors\nand a thimble were found upon him. These were\nidentified by the woman as her property.\nlp\nRIIRN $70000 CHURCH MGRTGAGE.\nTo celebrate the burning of a 370,600 mortgage the\ncongregation of the Calvary Methodist Episcopal\nChurch, at No. 2% Seventh avenue, gave a jubilee\ndinner last night in the Sunday school room of the\n%hurch. Among the guests wera Chancellor Day,\nof Syracuse University, John S. Huyler, Bishop\nDavid H. Moore. the Rev. Dr. F. H. Carpenter,\nthe Rev. Dr. C. M. Fowles and the Rev. Dr. Allan\nAfar ossie\nCRISCOM MORGAN'S HOST IN ROME.\npe\nRome, March 30. -The American Ambassador,\nLioyd C. Griscom, gave dinner and reception to\nnight in nonor of J. Pierpont Morgan and his\ndaughter, Mrs. H. Satterlee. Many of the (Cabi\npet ministers and ambassadors and many Ameri\ncuns were among the guests. One of the enjoyable\nfeatures of the evening was the singing of Mme.\nmma Nevada.\nFIRED AT SERGEANT, KILLED BOY.\n{By Telegraph to The Tribvre\nWilmington. Del, Marel. 30 John ook, thirteen\nvears ola, was shot and instantly killed at Fort\nDu Pont, near Delaware City to-night, by a bullet\nintended for a soldier. The bev was sitting in a\ncigar store, conducted by Sergeant lacey at the\nfort, when the bullet crashed through the window.\nThe lad sat beside Sergeant Blackburn, and as the\nlatter is reported to have nad trouble with the men\nunder him, tt is said the shot was mealit for aim.\nThe culprit ls pot kKiows.\n[Ey Telegraph to The Tritune.]\ni By Telegraph to The Tribune.\nHILL TO GO TO BERLIN\nTHE INCIDENT CLOSED.\nTHE INCIDENT CLOSED.\nOfficial Announcement Made After\nWhite House Conference.\nA A A _ _\u2014\u2014\u2014 E\u2014 __ A A Yi _\u2014 EO  \u2014_\u2014_\u2014_\u2014 EG _\u2014 A _\u2014_\u2014 _\u2014_\u2014\u2014 A i A. \u2014G\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014_\u2014 E\u2014\u2014_\u2014_\u2014\u2014\u2014\u2014_\u2014\u2014_\u2014\u2014 THR HE Ta Bm\nPy Ele FXUUSC CU UR ETFLITLL.\nWashington, March 30.\u2014With a view to bring\ning to a close the gossip connected with the\nreported disapproval in Berlin of the appoint\nment of Dr. David Jayne Hill as Ambassador to\nGermany and terminating the incident, Baron\nvon Sternburg, the German Ambassador, called\nat the White House to-night by appointment\nto see President Roosevelt and Secretary Root.\nAssistant Secretary Bacon also was present.\nAt the close of the conference the following\nstatement was given out:\nIn addition to the communication already\nmade public from the German Foreign Office,\nthe German Ambassador has alse conveyed to\nthe American government the assurance of the\nEmperor that there has never been any change\nin his attitude toward Mr. Hill, and his cordial\nwillingness to welcome Mr. Hill to Berlin. The\nEmperor's favorable opinion of Mr. Hill was\ncommunicated to the Washington administra\ntion last November, and his attitude has never\nchanged since.\nApparently some remarks in a casual conver\ncation have been distorted by gossip and exasg\ngerated by rumor so as to give a totally er\nroneous impression of the whole matter.\nThe two governments have never shared this\nmisunderstanding. The design of the President\nand the Secretary of State in choosing Mr. Hill\nwas to select the man who of all the men in\nthe diplomatic service was best fitted for this\nparticular place\u2014a place of the very first\norder in honor and responsibility, and one to\nwhich, therefore, it was deemed well to send a\nskilled diplomat, a student, a speaker, an au\nthority on international law, a learned German\nscholar who had served with signal ability as\nAssistant Secretary of State under John Hay\nand as foreign minister in two successive posts,\nin the last of which he had rendered marked\nservice in connection with the Hague peace con\nference. This purpose is and has always been\nfully appreciated by the Emperor personally and\nin Germany at large.\nThe nomination of Dr. Hill as ambassador to\nGermany will be sent to the Senate to-morrow,\naccording to the plan agreed on to-night. No\ntime has been fixed for the retirement of Am\nbassador Tower, but it is expected that Dr. Hill\nwill succeed him some time in May.\nIt was said to-night that the purpose of the\nadministration has been to make it evident that\nthe great diplomatic posts are not to be treated\nas places to be held only by millionaires, but, so\nfar as possible, as rewards for faithful service\nto the public in other offices. Thus the last four\nambassadors appointed\u2014Mr. Riddle to Russia,\nMr. Dudley to Brazil, Mr. O'Brien to Japan and\nDr. Hill to Germany\u2014have all been men of mod\nerate means who in previous places of less rank\nhad shown especial fitness for the performance\nof the duties of the higher posts to which they\nwere appointed. It was pointed out that every\nambassador now in the service has had previous\ndiplomatic experience, and most of them long\nand varied service, although in some cases the\nchief previous service of the man has been ren\ndered outside of diplomacy.\nThe administration has been particularly anx\nfous to have {t made evident in the case of Dr.\nHill, as in the cases of Mr. Riddle, Mr. O'Brien\nand others mentioned, that the possession of\nmerely moderate means was no bar to prefer\nment to the highest posts, and it is because of\nthis feeling that t \u00ab0 deeply regrets the failure\nof Congress to provide proper official residences\ntor ambassadors abroad. It was said to-night\nthat this failure militates directly in favor of the\nman of great wealth and against the man of\nsmaller means, and both permits and causes\nsuch violent contrasts in the scale of expenditure\nof successive incumbents of the same office and\nfosters just such gossip and trouble as occurred\nin the present instance.\nVenice, March 30.\u2014Th= German Emperor be\nfore leaving here for Corfu to-night sald that a\nsatisfactory settlement would be reached in con\nnection with the appointment of David Jayn=\nHill as American Ambassador to Berlin, as he\nhad no personal objection to him. The state\nment that Dr. Hill was opposed to Gergyany at\nthe Hague Conference he believed to be un\nfounded, Dr. Hill, as American Minister at The\nHague. having had little active part in the con\nference.\nLondon, March 31l.-\u2014-The London papers for the\nmost part refrain froma comment on the Hill ineci\ndent. \u201cThe Daily News,\u201d however, says that the\nEmperor's whisper carries further than the thun\nders of other men. \u2018\u2018It all goes to show,\u201d savs the\npaper, \u2018that the Emperor ought neither to write to\nhis friends nor talk freely at the dinner tablz, for\nhe is a man of impulsive temperament, and is\nsingularly unfitted for a role where discretion is\nthe supreme virtue.\u201d\n\u201cThe Daily Express\u2019 says: \u201cThe new diplomacy\nof the dinner table and ballroom is a palpable\narachronism. To have it recognized that a man is\nunfitted to be Amssador unless he is wealthy\nand consumed with a desire to spend on lavish e:n\ntertainments is to put back the hands of the clock\nof history. President Roosevelt will not be the\nman we take him for if he does not bring down the\nbig stick on this particular cabal.\u201d\nThe comments thus far display a considerable\nignorance of the facts. \u201cThe Globe\u201d revives the\nold accusation of \u2018\u2018shirtsleeve diplomacy\u2019 against\nthe United States, and savs, in this connection:\n\u201cThey quite forget that the older nations some\ntimes takes offence at their casual way of conduct\ning affairs. If Emperor William does withdraw his\nobjection he will have made a great mistake, for\nin international mattere it does not do to play fast\nLondon, March 31.--The London papers for the\nmost part refrain froma comment on the Hill ineci\ndent. \u201cThe Daily News,\u201d however, says that the\nEmperor's whisper carries further than the thun\nders of other men. \u2018\u2018It all goes to show,\u201d says the\npaper, \u2018that the Emperor ought neither te write to\nhis friends nor talk freely at the dinner tablz, for\nhe is a man of impulsive temperament, and is\nsingularly unfitted for a role where discretion is\nthe supreme virtue.\u201d\n\u201cThe Daily Express\u2019 says: \u201cThe new diplomacy\nof the dinner table and ballroom is a palpable\narachronism. To have it recognized that a man is\nunfitted to be Amissador unless he is wealthy\nand consumed with a desire to spend on lavish en\ntertainments is to put back the hands of the clock\nof history. President Roosevelt will not be the\nman we take him for if he does not bring down the\nbig stick on this particular cabal.\u201d\nThe comments thus far display a considerable\nignorance of the facts. \u201cThe Globe\u201d revives the\nold accusation of \u2018\u2018shirtsleeve diplomacy\u2019 against\nthe United States, and savs, in this connection:\n\u201cThey quite forget that the older nations some\ntimes takes offence at their casual way of conduct\ning affairs, If Emperor William does withdraw his\nobjection he will have made a great mistake, for\nin international matters it does not do to play fast\nand loose.\u201d\nREAL ESTATE BROKER KILLS HIMSELF\nJohn Milton Stanaland Believed to Have\nBeen Financially Embarrassed.\nJohn Milton Stanaland, a real estata broker, with\noffices at No. 130 Broadway, committed suicide ny\nshooting himself in his apartments, at No. 612 West\n138th street last night. It is believed that financial\nembarrassment unkEalanced him mentally. When\nha returned from his office he greeted his wife and\ntittle girl as usual and seemed in the best of\nspirits.\nWhile his wife was attending to the care of the\nevening meal the girl, who was playing the plano,\nheard the muffled report of two pistol shots, Stana\nland was found dead in the bathroom, with blood\n~omine from wouvnds in the temple and heart.\nA DENIAL BY SECRETARY ROOT.\nrRyv Telegraph to The Tribune\nRY a A a me\nOmaha, March 30.\u2014Secretary FElthu Root has\nwritten Congressman Hitcheock, of Omaha, deny\ning that he gave an interview to a Vienna news\npaper in which he was made to say that the flood\nof emigrants from Europe, including the Bohem\njans, are like the barbarian hordes whieh overran\nReme.\nThe Bohemians of Omaha asked Mr. Root,\nthrough Mr. Hitchcock, for an explanation and\nthe Secretary answered, \u201cThere never was such\nan interview. I never said to any one at any time\nthe things quoted in that Vienna paper.\u201d\n'T PAID LAWSON TO ADVERTISE.\n{By Telegraph to The Tribune.\nBoston, March 30.-\u2014-It is stated here to-day that\nMr. Lawson's profits in the Yukon gold deal on\nthe curb last week were $2,100,000, and that his ad\nvertising cost him $250,000. This establishes a new\nadvertising record and new record figures for curb\ndeals. He is said to be formulating plans now for\na $0,000,000 combination, to be tullowed by another\nof $420,008,\n4\nPARSONS OFFERS $2500.\nTen Equal Rewards for Conviction\nof Election Lac Violators.\nHerbert Parsons, of the Republican County\nCommittee, in the following communication\noffers ten rewards for evidence leading to the\narrest and conviction of persons violatirg the\nelection law at the primaries to-day:\n\n1 hereby offer ten rewards of $250 each for\nevidence which leads to the arrest and convic\ntion of any Person who votes illegally or aids\nor abets illegal voting, or the arrest and con\nviction of any inspector of election who violates\nor knowingly ,permits the violation of the pri\nmary election iaw at the Republican primaries\nto be held on Tuesday, March 31, 1908.\nfacing the biggest crisis of his political career.\nYesterday it was openly announced that seven\nof the twenty-three Assembly district leaders\nHERBERT PARSONS.\nPresident Republican County Committee.\nNo. Madison avenue.\nRAILROADS GET TIME.\ni\n\nNo Commodity Clause Prosecutions\nTill After Supreme Court Decision.\nWashington, March 30.\u2014The governmen\u00ae \u201cwill\nnot prosecute railroads for failure to comply\nwith the \u201ccommodity clause\u201d of the rate law\npending a decision of the Supreme Court. This\ndecision has been reached, it is understood, after\ncarefu! consideration by the President, and he\nhas accordingly directed the Department of Jus\ntice to bring a test case as soon as possible after\nMay 1, the day when the law forbidding rail\nroads to transport any articie or commodity\nother than timber, manufactured, mined or pro\nduced by such road, or in which it is directly or\nindirectly interested. goes into effect. Thus, anv\nrailroad that owns coal mines would be liable\nto prosecution should it carry its own coal to\nmarket\nThe President, it is stated, has no desire to in\ncrease the embarrassments of the railroads in\ntheir efforts to comply with the law, and as the\nquestion of the validity of the \u201c\u2018commuodity\nclause\u201d has been seriously raised by competent\nlegal opinion, it was thought best for all inter\nests involved that a prompt determination of\nthe question by the Supreme Court should be\nsought. It is understood that the railroads have\ngiven assurances.to the government that if the\ncourts decide against them they will immedi\nately and In good faith comply with the law.\nHEPBURN DEFEATED.\nCivic Federation Bill to Stay in\nJudiciary Committee.\n{Fromm The Tribune Bureau.]\nWashington, March 30.\u2014The complete domi\nnation of tine House by Speaker Cannon has\nonce more been demonstrated, this time to the\ngreat discomfiture of Representative Hepburn,\nchairman of the Committee on Interstate Com\nmerce. As has been told in these dispatches,\nColonel Hepburn was seriously aggrieved when\nthe Speaker referred his bill amending the anti\ntrust law, popularly known as the Civic Federa\ntion bill, te the Committee on Judiciary, of\nwhich Colonel Hepburn has said, \u201cNo three of\nits members have ever been known to agree on\nanything.\u201d\nOn Saturday Colonel! Hepburn began the cir\nculation of a resolution overruling the Speaker,\ndischarging the Judiciary Committee from\nfurther consideration of the Hepburn bill and re\nferring it to the Interstate Commerce Commit\ntee. He was of the opinion that it would be an\neasy matter to obtain sufficient support for this\nresolution to insure its adoption, but to-day he\nwas compelled to give up in disgust. So pow\nerful is the influence of the Speaker that mem\nbers do not dare oppose him, and even the mem\nbers of Colonel Hepburn's own committee were\nafraid to support the resolution. Consequently,\nthe anti-trust bill will remain in the Judiciary\nCommittee until an agreement can be reached.\nand there are those who say that will be long\nafter the next Presidential campaign has been\nfought and won\nMORE ARRESTS IN HAYTLI.\nSir Officers, Including Larraque,\nSeek Refuee in Lezations.\nPort-au-Prince, March 30. Numerous arrests\nwere made here last night and to-day of officers\nsuspected of complicity in the latest conspiracy,\nof which General! Larraque, chief of the cavalry,\nwas alleged to be the leader.\nThe Haytian government announces its in\ntention of giving these prisoners a hearing be\nfore the civil courts, and declares that no sum\nmary executions will take place.\nSquads of soldiers are continuing their search\nof houses in quest of fugitives Five officers,\nincluding General Larraque, have taken refuge\nin the French Legation, and one officer in the\n(yerman l.egation.\nTRIES TO KILI WIFE.\nBrooklyn Man Then Takes His\nO:en Life.\nEdward F. Randall, who lives at No. 701 Park\nPlace, Brooklyn, shot his wife, Rose, in tha\nright jaw and loft hand last night and then com\nmitted suicide. Mre. Randall, although in a\nserious condition at the Swedish Hospital, is ex\npected to live.\n\nThe neighbors heard three shots shortly after\n10 o'clock last night, and saw Mrs. Randall run\nfrom her home to the house next door. Sher\nsaid: \u201cMy husband is trying to kill me.\u201d Upon\nhearing this a few persons ran into the Randall\nhome and found the husband lying dead.\nThe neighbors said that Mr. and Mrs. Randall\nalways appeared to be a happy pair, and did not\nknow of any reason for the deed.\nMr. Randall's insurance policy, made out to\nhis wife, was found on the mantel, also a letter\nwritten to him by his niece, who is said to be\nan inmate of some deaf and dumb asylum in\nNew York.\nRandall, it is sald, was an expert accountant.\nTAFT SPLITS ILLINOIS DISTRICT.\nCannon Supporters, Defeated, Will Elect\nTNaleeates at Separate Convention.\nChicago, March 30.\u2014A contesting delegation to\nthe Republican National Convention is promised\nfrom the lst Cengress District of Illinois as a re\nault of a split In the district convention to-night.\nDaniel J. Schuyler, jr. and Chauncey Dewey were\nchosen delegates and instructed to work for the\nnomination of William H. Taft as Presidential\ncandidate, with about fifty of the 131 delegates\nrefusing to vote after a resolution indorsing Joseph\nG. Cannon as Presidential canlidate nad been de\nolared lost. The supporcers of Mr. Cannon held a\nnew convention after the adjournment of the first\ngathering, effected an organization and aleurned\nsubject to call to select delegates to the national\nconvention.\nthe state committee. McCarren defied the com\nmittee a year and a half ago and is only a\nmember now because of an injunction.\u2122\nTHE BYRNES DEFECTION.\nThe breaking away of Thomas F. Byrnes from\nRepublicans of the 4th Congress District also\nheld a convention to-night. David E. Shanahan\nand Swan Norman were selected as delegates to\nthe national convention and instructed to vote fur\nJoseph UG, Cannon as Presidential nominee.\n\n\nMeCerren caused a great deal of comment mn\nController Metz's office yesterday. Mr. Byrnes\nholds a responsible position in the real estate\ndivision. Mr. Byrnes said: \u201cThis is a movement\ninside the family and for the good of the\nCRISIS FOR \u201cLONG PAT\u201d\nMURPHY IN BROOKLYN.\nSev\u00e9n Leaders Already in Line\nAgainst McCarren.\nIt is now certain that Patrick H. McCarren is\nand that five or six others were on the verge of\nfollowing their example.\nFriday evening's secret meeting at the Astor\nHouse passed a resolution saying in substance\nthat the Democratic county and borough can\ndidates had been defeated at every election in\nthe last four years, though the Democratic en\nrolment was greater than that of any other\nlocal organization; that the opposition te Me\nCarren was now organized in every Assembly\ndistrict with the sole object of forcing him from\nthe leadership, and that harmony in the ranks\ncould oniy be obtained by a reorganization of\nthe party in Kings County.\nThe men who signed the resolution are Will\njam E. Melody, leader of the 4th Assembly Dis\ntrict: William R. McGuire, of the \u00e9th, William\nA. Doyle, 9th; Thomas R. Farrell, 10th;\nThomas F. Byrnes, 11th; James P. Sinnott, 22d,\nand Patrick F. Lynch, 23d. The leaders who\nare believed to be on the point of joining the\n\u201cantis\u201d are Michael E. Butler, of the 12th]\nJames S. Regan, 5th; J. Morressey Gray, 3th;\nPolice Magistrate John Naumer, 17th, and\nJames Kane. 3\u00e9. The anti-McCarren fights su\nperintended by Borough President Coler, James\nShevlin and Michael J. Flaherty have been\ncalled off in the districts led by the signers of\nthe resolution, and the fights in the other dis\ntricts will be dropped as their leaders join tha\n\u201cantis.\u201d\nWHAT IS BEHIND MOVEMENT.\nhad openly thrown in their lot with the\n\n\ni\nThe question that was asked by peliticans all\nabout the borough yesterday was, \u201cWhat is be\nhind this opposition movement? What has\ngiven it the power to turn seven leaders against\nMcCarren?\u201d\nThe answer to the puzzle seems to be that\nTammany Hall has again decided to attack Me\nCarren. It was noted with Interest that among\nthe seven who signed the resolution was Doyle,\nwho represented Tammany in the last big fight\nagaimst McCarren three years ago. At that tima\nthe opposition to McCarren was not half so\nstrong or well organized as at present. At that\ntime the fight was engineered by Tammany.\nThree or four leaders who were still stand\ning with \u201cBoss\u201d Hugh McLaughlin joined the\nopposition. Doyle stuck out for five or six\nmonths, made a bad showing at the primaries\nand then made overtures to \u201cLong Pat\u201d and re\nturned to the regular ranks. Doyle's fight was\nhopeless from start to finish.\nThe present fight is in strong contrast with\nDoyle's. The antis are organized in every dis\ntrict. They nave good leaders in the threa\nstrongest anti-McCarren men in the borough.\nthey have the borough patronage and of late\nTammany patronage. Only a few days ago City\nClerk Scully, who is a Tammany man, appointed\na half dozen clerks for the Brookiyn marriages\nlicense bureau. All were antis. When the pro\nposal to build \u2018the Fourth avenue subway cama\nup before the Board of Aldermen last week\nTammany again stood with Coler against Con\ntroller Metz and Mayor McClellan.\nHAND OF \u201cLITTLE TIM.\u201d\n\u201cLittle Tim\u201d Sullivan was supposed to have\npassed around the word then, and he iz believed\nto have had much to do with the conversion of\nthe seven to anti-McCarren ideas Even Me\nClellan is said to be ready to stand aside and\nwatch developments. He is ready to recognize\nthe winning party, it is understood.\nOmeeotf the leaders of the antis said yesterday:\n\u201cWe saw the handwriting on the wall when\nMurphy sent word to Scully to appoint anti\nMcCarren men in the City Clerk's office. This,\ntogether with the alliance with the Mayor, put\nus wise. I don\u2018t know who'll be the nominal\nleader. but the real leader will be Murphy.\u201d\nMr. Coler denies that Murphy or any other\noutsider is having anything whatever to do with\nthe present fight. He issued a statement yester\nday in which he said, after telling about the\nresolution and the seven signers, that the antis\nare fighting solely to down McCarren, and that\nno one has been picked to succeed him.\nHe said later: \u201cWe wish it known that we\nstand for the autonomy and political indepen\ndence of Kings County Demecracy. Sur unal\nterable principle is that the Democratic organi\nzation of Kings shall be and shall remain co\nordinate with that of New York County and of\nequal authority.\nWARNING BY MR COLER.\n\u201cMcCarren and Metz do not stand for county\nand borough autonomy. as they showed when\nthey signed away all borough rights in the pro\nposed charter revision McCarren has to-day\nchanged inspectors in several districts and\nplaced racetrack sheet writers on the job. He\nbelieves that these men will be willing to take\na chance. but I want te warn these men and\nall others that the police will see to it that there\nis fair play at the primaries. If there is any\nattempt at fraud of any sort those who maka\nthe attempt will do time. I have definite knowl\nedge on this subject.\u201d\nTwenty-six police captains of Brooklyn and\nQueens have been shifted over primary day by\nCommissioner Bingham, and there is evidenca\nthat the police will make a special effort to pre\nserve order at the polls.\nMcCarren learned of the resolution on Sat\nurday afternoon, receiving the information, from\none of the leaders who signed it. There has\nbeen no attempt to get his supporters together\nas vet.\nThe seven held a secret meeting on Sunday\nafternoon. They said vesterdayv that they would\ncarry enough of the Assembiy districts te cop\ntrol the executive committee. The districts that\nthey are sure of are the 1st, 2d, 3d, Sth, 10th,\n17th and 18th, besides their own. The Tead\ners in most of these districts are about ready\nto join the \u201cantis\u2122 and have the fights against\nthem called off. If they prophesy correctly,\nthey will cortrol! fourteen of the twenty-three\ndistricts.\nIt was said yesterday that the next move\nwould be to request the state committee to rec\u00ab\nognize the party in Breokliyn. Said an \u201canti\nvesterday: \u201cThe other leaders will come in\nwhen they discover that the state committes\nwill not recognize the McCarren delegation to\nthe state convention and that after the\nconvention the state committee intends to clean\nhouse over here. That will finish McCarren In\nPSE ae, hum Te meme TemeprowmoG Tima\nha\nalways made it a point to be on good terms with\nPA NNN ERNE NN ATOR maha","height":"35592","width":"25700"}}
